[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In object-oriented programming, **inheritance** is the mechanism of basing an object or class upon another object (prototype-based inheritance) or class (class-based inheritance), retaining similar implementation.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is also defined as deriving new classes (sub classes) from existing ones such as super class or base class and then forming them into a hierarchy of classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In most class-based object-oriented languages like C++, an object created through inheritance, a "child object", acquires all the properties and behaviors of the "parent object", with the exception of: constructors, destructors, overloaded operators and friend functions of the base class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance allows programmers to create classes that are built upon existing classes, to specify a new implementation while maintaining the same behaviors (realizing an interface), to reuse code and to independently extend original software via public classes and interfaces.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The relationships of objects or classes through inheritance give rise to a directed acyclic graph.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An inherited class is called a **subclass** of its parent class or super class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Class-modifying inheritance patterns can be pre-defined according to simple network interface parameters such that inter-language compatibility is preserved.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance should not be confused with subtyping.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In some languages, generally statically-typed class-based OO languages, like C++, C#, Java, and Scala, inheritance and subtyping agree, whereas in others they differ.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In general, subtyping establishes an *is-a* relationship, whereas inheritance only reuses implementation and establishes a syntactic relationship, not necessarily a semantic relationship (inheritance does not ensure behavioral subtyping).
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] To distinguish these concepts, subtyping is sometimes referred to as *interface inheritance* (without acknowledging that the specialization of type variables also induces a subtyping relation), whereas inheritance as defined here is known as *implementation inheritance* or *code inheritance*.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Still, inheritance is a commonly used mechanism for establishing subtype relationships.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is contrasted with object composition, where one object *contains* another object (or objects of one class contain objects of another class); see composition over inheritance.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In contrast to subtyping’s *is-a* relationship, composition implements a *has-a* relationship.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Mathematically speaking, inheritance in any system of classes induces a strict partial order on the set of classes in that system.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In 1966, Tony Hoare presented some remarks on records, and in particular, the idea of record subclasses, record types with common properties but discriminated by a variant tag and having fields private to the variant.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Influenced by this, in 1967 Ole-Johan Dahl and Kristen Nygaard presented a design that allowed specifying objects that belonged to different classes but had common properties.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The common properties were collected in a superclass, and each superclass could itself potentially have a superclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The values of a subclass were thus compound objects, consisting of some number of prefix parts belonging to various superclasses, plus a main part belonging to the subclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] These parts were all concatenated together.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The attributes of a compound object would be accessible by dot notation.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This idea was first adopted in the Simula 67 programming language.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The idea then spread to Smalltalk, C++, Java, Python, and many other languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] There are various types of inheritance, based on paradigm and specific language.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where subclasses inherit the features of one superclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A class acquires the properties of another class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where one class can have more than one superclass and inherit features from all parent classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] where a subclass is inherited from another subclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is not uncommon that a class is derived from another derived class as shown in the figure "Multilevel inheritance".
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This process can be extended to any number of levels.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This is where one class serves as a superclass (base class) for more than one sub class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, a parent class, A, can have two subclasses B and C.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Both B and C's parent class is A, but B and C are two separate subclasses.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Hybrid inheritance is when a mix of two or more of the above types of inheritance occurs.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An example of this is when a class A has a subclass B which has two subclasses, C and D.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This is a mixture of both multilevel inheritance and hierarchal inheritance.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The colon indicates that the subclass inherits from the superclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The visibility modifier is optional and, if present, may be either *private* or *public*.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The default visibility (if there is no modifier present) is *private*.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Visibility specifies whether the features of the base class are *privately derived* or *publicly derived*.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Some languages also support the inheritance of other constructs.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, in Eiffel, contracts that define the specification of a class are also inherited by heirs.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The superclass establishes a common interface and foundational functionality, which specialized subclasses can inherit, modify, and supplement.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The software inherited by a subclass is considered reused in the subclass.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A reference to an instance of a class may actually be referring to one of its subclasses.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The actual class of the object being referenced is impossible to predict at compile-time.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A uniform interface is used to invoke the member functions of objects of a number of different classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Subclasses may replace superclass functions with entirely new functions that must share the same method signature.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In some languages a class may be declared as non-subclassable by adding certain class modifiers to the class declaration.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Examples include the `final` keyword in Java and C++11 onwards or the `sealed` keyword in C#.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Such modifiers are added to the class declaration before the `class` keyword and the class identifier declaration.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Such non-subclassable classes restrict reusability, particularly when developers only have access to precompiled binaries and not source code.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Just as classes may be non-subclassable, method declarations may contain method modifiers that prevent the method from being overridden (i.e. replaced with a new function with the same name and type signature in a subclass).
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A private method is un-overridable simply because it is not accessible by classes other than the class it is a member function of (this is not true for C++, though).
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] A `final` method in Java, a `sealed` method in C# or a `frozen` feature in Eiffel cannot be overridden.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] If a superclass method is a virtual method, then invocations of the superclass method will be dynamically dispatched.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Some languages require that method be specifically declared as virtual (e.g.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] C++), and in others, all methods are virtual (e.g.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An invocation of a non-virtual method will always be statically dispatched (i.e. the address of the function call is determined at compile-time).
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Static dispatch is faster than dynamic dispatch and allows optimizations such as inline expansion.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The following table shows which variables and functions get inherited dependent on the visibility given when deriving the class, using the terminology established by C++.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is used to co-relate two or more classes to each other.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Many object-oriented programming languages permit a class or object to replace the implementation of an aspect—typically a behavior—that it has inherited.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Overriding introduces a complication: which version of the behavior does an instance of the inherited class use—the one that is part of its own class, or the one from the parent (base) class?
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The answer varies between programming languages, and some languages provide the ability to indicate that a particular behavior is not to be overridden and should behave as defined by the base class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For instance, in C#, the base method or property can only be overridden in a subclass if it is marked with the virtual, abstract, or override modifier, while in programming languages such as Java, different methods can be called to override other methods.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An alternative to overriding is hiding the inherited code.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Implementation inheritance is the mechanism whereby a subclass re-uses code in a base class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] By default the subclass retains all of the operations of the base class, but the subclass may override some or all operations, replacing the base-class implementation with its own.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In the following example, subclasses `SquareSumComputer` and `CubeSumComputer` override the `transform()` method of the base class `SumComputer`.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The base class comprises operations to compute the sum of the squares between two integers.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The subclass re-uses all of the functionality of the base class with the exception of the operation that transforms a number into its square, replacing it with an operation that transforms a number into its square and cube respectively.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The subclasses therefore compute the sum of the squares/cubes between two integers.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In most quarters, class inheritance for the sole purpose of code reuse has fallen out of favor.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The primary concern is that implementation inheritance does not provide any assurance of polymorphic substitutability—an instance of the reusing class cannot necessarily be substituted for an instance of the inherited class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] An alternative technique, explicit delegation, requires more programming effort, but avoids the substitutability issue.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In C++ private inheritance can be used as a form of *implementation inheritance* without substitutability.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Whereas public inheritance represents an "is-a" relationship and delegation represents a "has-a" relationship, private (and protected) inheritance can be thought of as an "is implemented in terms of" relationship.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another frequent use of inheritance is to guarantee that classes maintain a certain common interface; that is, they implement the same methods.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The parent class can be a combination of implemented operations and operations that are to be implemented in the child classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Often, there is no interface change between the supertype and subtype- the child implements the behavior described instead of its parent class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is similar to but distinct from subtyping.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Subtyping enables a given type to be substituted for another type or abstraction and is said to establish an *is-a* relationship between the subtype and some existing abstraction, either implicitly or explicitly, depending on language support.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The relationship can be expressed explicitly via inheritance in languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, the following C++ code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes *B* and *A*, where *B* is both a subclass and a subtype of *A* and can be used as an *A* wherever a *B* is specified (via a reference, a pointer or the object itself).
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] In programming languages that do not support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism, the relationship between a base class and a derived class is only a relationship between implementations (a mechanism for code reuse), as compared to a relationship between types.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Inheritance, even in programming languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism, does not necessarily entail behavioral subtyping.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] It is entirely possible to derive a class whose object will behave incorrectly when used in a context where the parent class is expected; see the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] (Compare connotation/denotation.) In some OOP languages, the notions of code reuse and subtyping coincide because the only way to declare a subtype is to define a new class that inherits the implementation of another.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Using inheritance extensively in designing a program imposes certain constraints.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, consider a class `Person` that contains a person's name, date of birth, address and phone number.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] We can define a subclass of Person called `Student` that contains the person's grade point average and classes taken, and another subclass of Person called Employee that contains the person's job-title, employer, and salary.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The composite reuse principle is an alternative to inheritance.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This technique supports polymorphism and code reuse by separating behaviors from the primary class hierarchy and including specific behavior classes as required in any business domain class.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] This approach avoids the static nature of a class hierarchy by allowing behavior modifications at run time and allows one class to implement behaviors buffet-style, instead of being restricted to the behaviors of its ancestor classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Implementation inheritance has been controversial among programmers and theoreticians of object-oriented programming since at least the 1990s.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Among the critics are the authors of *Design Patterns*, who advocate instead for interface inheritance, and favor composition over inheritance.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] For example, the decorator pattern (as mentioned above) has been proposed to overcome the static nature of inheritance between classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] As a more fundamental solution to the same problem, role-oriented programming introduces a distinct relationship, *played-by*, combining properties of inheritance and composition into a new concept.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] According to Allen Holub, the main problem with implementation inheritance is that it introduces unnecessary coupling in the form of the "fragile base class problem": modifications to the base class implementation can cause inadvertent behavioral changes in subclasses.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Using interfaces avoids this problem because no implementation is shared, only the API.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another way of stating this is that "inheritance breaks encapsulation".
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] The problem surfaces clearly in open object-oriented systems such as frameworks, where client code is expected to inherit from system-supplied classes and then substituted for the system's classes in its algorithms.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Reportedly, Java inventor James Gosling has spoken against implementation inheritance, stating that he would not include it if he were to redesign Java.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Language designs that decouple inheritance from subtyping (interface inheritance) appeared as early as 1990; a modern example of this is the Go programming language.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Complex inheritance, or inheritance used within an insufficiently mature design, may lead to the yo-yo problem.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] When inheritance was used as a primary approach to structure programs in the late 1990s, developers tended to break code into more layers of inheritance as the system functionality grew.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] If a development team combined multiple layers of inheritance with the single responsibility principle, this resulted in many very thin layers of code, with many layers consisting of only 1 or 2 lines of actual code.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Too many layers make debugging a significant challenge, as it becomes hard to determine which layer needs to be debugged.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Another issue with inheritance is that subclasses must be defined in code, which means that program users cannot add new subclasses at runtime.
[src:prototype-pollution/inheritance-object-oriented-programming] Other design patterns (such as Entity–component–system) allow program users to define variations of an entity at runtime.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:prototype-pollution/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet lists actions developers can take to develop secure Node.js applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Each item has a brief explanation and solution that is specific to the Node.js environment.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js applications are increasing in number and they are no different from other frameworks and programming languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js applications are prone to all kinds of web application vulnerabilities.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet aims to provide a list of best practices to follow during development of Node.js applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are several recommendations to enhance security of your Node.js applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Asynchronous callback functions are one of the strongest features of Node.js.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, increasing layers of nesting within callback functions can become a problem.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Any multistage process can become nested 10 or more levels deep.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This problem is referred to as a "Pyramid of Doom" or "Callback Hell".
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In such code, the errors and results get lost within the callback.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Promises are a good way to write asynchronous code without getting into nested pyramids.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Promises provide top-down execution while being asynchronous by delivering errors and results to next `.then` function.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Another advantage of Promises is the way Promises handle errors.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] If an error occurs in a Promise class, it skips over the `.then` functions and invokes the first `.catch` function it finds.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This way Promises provide a higher assurance of capturing and handling errors.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As a principle, you can make all your asynchronous code (apart from emitters) return promises.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It should be noted that Promise calls can also become a pyramid.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to completely stay away from "Callback Hell", flat Promise chains should be used.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] If the module you are using does not support Promises, you can convert base object to a Promise by using `Promise.promisifyAll()` function.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Buffering and parsing of request bodies can be a resource intensive task.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] If there is no limit on the size of requests, attackers can send requests with large request bodies that can exhaust server memory and/or fill disk space.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You can limit the request body size for all requests using raw-body.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, fixing a request size limit for all requests may not be the correct behavior, since some requests may have a large payload in the request body, such as when uploading a file.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, input with a JSON type is more dangerous than a multipart input, since parsing JSON is a blocking operation.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, you should set request size limits for different content types.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It should be noted that attackers can change the `Content-Type` header of the request and bypass request size limits.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, before processing the request, data contained in the request should be validated against the content type stated in the request headers.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] If content type validation for each request affects the performance severely, you can only validate specific content types or request larger than a predetermined size.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js is very different from common application platforms that use threads.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js has a single-thread event-driven architecture.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] By means of this architecture, throughput becomes high and the programming model becomes simpler.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js is implemented around a non-blocking I/O event loop.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] With this event loop, there is no waiting on I/O or context switching.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The event loop looks for events and dispatches them to handler functions.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Because of this, when CPU intensive JavaScript operations are executed, the event loop waits for them to finish.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This is why such operations are called "blocking".
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] To overcome this problem, Node.js allows assigning callbacks to IO-blocked events.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This way, the main application is not blocked and callbacks run asynchronously.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, as a general principle, all blocking operations should be done asynchronously so that the event loop is not blocked.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Even if you perform blocking operations asynchronously, your application may still not serve as expected.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This happens if there is a code outside the callback that relies on the code within the callback to run first.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In the above example, `unlinkSync` function may run before the callback, which will delete the file before the desired actions on the file content is done.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Such race conditions can also affect the security of your application.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] An example would be a scenario where authentication is performed in a callback and authenticated actions are run synchronously.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to eliminate such race conditions, you can write all operations that rely on each other in a single non-blocking function.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] By doing so, you can guarantee that all operations are executed in the correct order.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In the above code, call to unlink the file and other file operations are within the same callback.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This provides the correct order of operations.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Input validation is a crucial part of application security.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Input validation failures can result in many types of application attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] These include SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting, Command Injection, Local/Remote File Inclusion, Denial of Service, Directory Traversal, LDAP Injection and many other injection attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to avoid these attacks, input to your application should be sanitized first.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The best input validation technique is to use a list of accepted inputs.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, if this is not possible, input should be first checked against expected input scheme and dangerous inputs should be escaped.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to ease input validation in Node.js applications, there are some modules like validator and express-mongo-sanitize.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For detailed information on input validation, please refer to Input Validation Cheat Sheet.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] JavaScript is a dynamic language and depending on how the framework parses a URL, the data seen by the application code can take many forms.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In addition to input validation, you should escape all HTML and JavaScript content shown to users via application in order to prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For context-aware escaping, use escape-html.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When you need to render user-supplied HTML (rather than escape it), use a maintained sanitizer such as DOMPurify (with `jsdom` for server-side use) or `sanitize-html`.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Avoid `node-esapi`, which is no longer actively maintained.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Logging application activity is an encouraged good practice.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It makes it easier to debug any errors encountered during application runtime.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It is also useful for security concerns, since it can be used during incident response.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In addition, these logs can be used to feed Intrusion Detection/Prevention Systems (IDS/IPS).
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In Node.js, there are modules such as Winston, Bunyan, or Pino to perform application activity logging.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] These modules enable streaming and querying logs, and they provide a way to handle uncaught exceptions.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You can provide different transports so that you can save errors to a separate log file and general application logs to a different log file.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Additional information on security logging can be found in Logging Cheat Sheet.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When your application server is under heavy network traffic, it may not be able to serve its users.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This is essentially a type of Denial of Service (DoS) attack.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The toobusy-js module allows you to monitor the event loop.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It keeps track of the response time, and when it goes beyond a certain threshold, this module can indicate your server is too busy.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In that case, you can stop processing incoming requests and send them `503 Server Too Busy` message so that your application stay responsive.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Brute-forcing is a common threat to all web applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Attackers can use brute-forcing as a password guessing attack to obtain account passwords.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, application developers should take precautions against brute-force attacks especially in login pages.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js has several modules available for this purpose.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Express-bouncer, express-brute and rate-limiter are just some examples.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Based on your needs and requirements, you should choose one or more of these modules and use accordingly.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Express-bouncer and express-brute modules work similarly.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] They increase the delay for each failed request and can be arranged for a specific route.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Apart from express-bouncer and express-brute, the rate-limiter module can also help to prevent brute-forcing attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It enables specifying how many requests a specific IP address can make during a specified time period.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] CAPTCHA usage is also another common mechanism used against brute-forcing.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are modules developed for Node.js CAPTCHAs.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] A common module used in Node.js applications is svg-captcha.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Account lockout is a recommended solution to keep attackers away from your valid users.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Account lockout is possible with many modules like mongoose.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You can refer to this blog post to see how account lockout is implemented in mongoose.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) aims to perform authorized actions on behalf of an authenticated user, while the user is unaware of this action.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] CSRF attacks are generally performed for state-changing requests like changing a password, adding users or placing orders.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Csurf is an express middleware that has been used to mitigate CSRF attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] But a security hole in this package has been recently discovered.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The team behind the package has not fixed the discovered vulnerability and they have marked the package as deprecated, recommending using any other CSRF protection package.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For detailed information on cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks and prevention methods, you can refer to Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] A web application should not contain any page that is not used by users, as it may increase the attack surface of the application.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, all unused API routes should be disabled in Node.js applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This occurs especially in frameworks like Sails and Feathers, as they automatically generate REST API endpoints.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For example, in Sails, if a URL does not match a custom route, it may match one of the automatic routes and still generate a response.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This situation may lead to results ranging from information leakage to arbitrary command execution.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, before using such frameworks and modules, it is important to know the routes they automatically generate and remove or disable these routes.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] HTTP Parameter Pollution(HPP) is an attack in which attackers send multiple HTTP parameters with the same name and this causes your application to interpret them unpredictably.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When multiple parameter values are sent, Express populates them in an array.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to solve this issue, you can use hpp module.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When used, this module will ignore all values submitted for a parameter in `req.query` and/or `req.body` and just select the last parameter value submitted.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Information about the users of an application is among the most critical information about the application.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] User tables generally include fields like ID, username, full name, email address, birth date, password and in some cases social security numbers.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, when querying and using user objects, you need to return only needed fields as it may be vulnerable to personal information disclosure.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This is also correct for other objects stored on the database.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] If you just need a certain field of an object, you should only return the specific fields required.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As an example, you can use a function like the following whenever you need to get information on a user.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] By doing so, you can only return the fields that are needed for your specific operation.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In other words, if you only need to list names of the users available, you are not returning their email addresses or credit card numbers in addition to their full names.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Object properties include three hidden attributes: `writable` (if false, property value cannot be changed), `enumerable` (if false, property cannot be used in for loops) and `configurable` (if false, property cannot be deleted).
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When defining an object property through assignment, these three hidden attributes are set to true by default.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Apart from these, there are some special functions for object attributes.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] `Object.preventExtensions()` prevents new properties from being added to the object.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Authorization prevents users from acting outside of their intended permissions.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to do so, users and their roles should be determined with consideration of the principle of least privilege.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Each user role should only have access to the resources they must use.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For your Node.js applications, you can use the acl module to provide ACL (access control list) implementation.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] With this module, you can create roles and assign users to these roles.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Starting with Node.js v20, a Permission Model is available to restrict application privileges.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As of Node.js v23.5.0, the model is considered stable and can be enabled using the `--permission` flag (earlier versions require `--experimental-permission`).
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Use `--allow‑fs‑read` to specify which files or directories Node.js is allowed to read.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For more details refer to the official documentation.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Node.js behavior for uncaught exceptions is to print current stack trace and then terminate the thread.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, Node.js allows customization of this behavior.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It provides a global object named process that is available to all Node.js applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It is an EventEmitter object and in case of an uncaught exception, uncaughtException event is emitted and it is brought up to the main event loop.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to provide a custom behavior for uncaught exceptions, you can bind to this event.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, resuming the application after such an uncaught exception can lead to further problems.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, if you do not want to miss any uncaught exception, you should bind to uncaughtException event and cleanup any allocated resources like file descriptors, handles and similar before shutting down the process.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Resuming the application is strongly discouraged as the application will be in an unknown state.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It is important to note that when displaying error messages to the user in case of an uncaught exception, detailed information like stack traces should not be revealed to the user.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Instead, custom error messages should be shown to the users in order not to cause any information leakage.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When using EventEmitter, errors can occur anywhere in the event chain.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Normally, if an error occurs in an EventEmitter object, an error event that has an Error object as an argument is called.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, if there are no attached listeners to that error event, the Error object that is sent as an argument is thrown and becomes an uncaught exception.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In short, if you do not handle errors within an EventEmitter object properly, these unhandled errors may crash your application.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, you should always listen to error events when using EventEmitter objects.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Errors that occur within asynchronous callbacks are easy to miss.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, as a general principle first argument to the asynchronous calls should be an Error object.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, express routes handle errors itself, but it should be always remembered that errors occurred in asynchronous calls made within express routes are not handled, unless an Error object is sent as a first argument.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Errors in these callbacks can be propagated as many times as possible.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Each callback that the error has been propagated to can ignore, handle or propagate the error.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Generally, session information is sent using cookies in web applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, improper use of HTTP cookies can render an application to several session management vulnerabilities.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Some flags can be set for each cookie to prevent these kinds of attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] `httpOnly`, `Secure` and `SameSite` flags are very important for session cookies.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] `httpOnly` flag prevents the cookie from being accessed by client-side JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This is an effective counter-measure for XSS attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] `Secure` flag lets the cookie to be sent only if the communication is over HTTPS.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] `SameSite` flag can prevent cookies from being sent in cross-site requests that helps protect against Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Apart from these, there are other flags like domain, path and expires.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Setting these flags appropriately is encouraged, but they are mostly related to cookie scope not the cookie security.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are several HTTP security headers that can help you prevent some common attack vectors.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The top-level `helmet` function is a wrapper around 14 smaller middlewares.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For moderns browsers, it is recommended to implement a strong **Content-Security-Policy** policy, as detailed in the next section.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As this middleware performs very little validation, it is recommended to rely on CSP checkers like CSP Evaluator instead.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The above code sets Cache-Control, Surrogate-Control, Pragma and Expires headers accordingly.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, you can lie about the technologies used with this header.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For example, even if your application does not use PHP, you can set X-Powered-By header to seem so.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Security of your application depends directly on how secure the third-party packages you use in your application are.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Therefore, it is important to keep your packages up-to-date.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It should be noted that Using Components with Known Vulnerabilities is still in the OWASP Top 10.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You can use OWASP Dependency-Check to see if any of the packages used in the project has a known vulnerability.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, you can use Retire.js to check JavaScript libraries with known vulnerabilities.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are several other tools you can use to check your dependencies.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] A more comprehensive list can be found in Vulnerable Dependency Management CS.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are some JavaScript functions that are dangerous and should only be used where necessary or unavoidable.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The first example is the `eval()` function.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This function takes a string argument and executes it as any other JavaScript source code.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Combined with user input, this behavior inherently leads to remote code execution vulnerability.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Similarly, calls to `child_process.exec` are also very dangerous.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This function acts as a bash interpreter and sends its arguments to /bin/sh.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] By injecting input to this function, attackers can execute arbitrary commands on the server.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In addition to these functions, some modules require special care when being used.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As an example, `fs` module handles filesystem operations.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, if improperly sanitized user input is fed into this module, your application may become vulnerable to file inclusion and directory traversal vulnerabilities.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Similarly, `vm` module provides APIs for compiling and running code within V8 Virtual Machine contexts.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Since it can perform dangerous actions by nature, it should be used within a sandbox.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It would not be fair to say that these functions and modules should not be used whatsoever, however, they should be used carefully especially when they use with user input.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, there are some other functions that may render your application vulnerable.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) is a Denial of Service attack, that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size).
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) is a type of Denial of Service attack that uses regular expressions.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Some Regular Expression (Regex) implementations cause extreme situations that makes the application very slow.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Attackers can use such regex implementations to cause application to get into these extreme situations and hang for a long time.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Such regexes are called evil if application can be stuck on crafted input.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Generally, these regexes are exploited by grouping with repetition and alternation with overlapping.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] For example, the following regular expression `^(([a-z])+.)+[A-Z]([a-z])+$` can be used to specify Java class names.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] However, a very long string (aaaa...aaaaAaaaaa...aaaa) can also match with this regular expression.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] There are some tools to check if a regex has a potential for causing denial of service.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] When developing code, keeping all security tips in mind can be really difficult.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Also, keeping all team members obey these rules is nearly impossible.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This is why there are Static Analysis Security Testing (SAST) tools.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] These tools do not execute your code, but they simply look for patterns that can contain security risks.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] As JavaScript is a dynamic and loosely-typed language, linting tools are really essential in the software development life cycle.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] The linting rules should be reviewed periodically and the findings should be audited.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Another advantage of these tools is the feature that you can add custom rules for patterns that you may see dangerous.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] ESLint and JSHint are commonly used SAST tools for JavaScript linting.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] JavaScript has a number of unsafe and dangerous legacy features that should not be used.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to remove these features, ES5 included a strict mode for developers.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] With this mode, errors that were silent previously are thrown.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] It also helps JavaScript engines perform optimizations.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] With strict mode, previously accepted bad syntax causes real errors.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] Because of these improvements, you should always use strict mode in your application.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In order to enable strict mode, you just need to write `"use strict";` on top of your code.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] This list mainly focuses on issues that are common in Node.js applications, with recommendations and examples.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] In addition to these, there are general security by design principles that apply to web applications regardless of technologies used in application server.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You should also keep those principles in mind while developing your applications.
[src:prototype-pollution/nodejs-security-cheat-sheet] You can always refer to OWASP Cheat Sheet Series to learn more about web application vulnerabilities and mitigation techniques used against them.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] In software development, an **object** is a semantic entity that has state, behavior, and identity.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] An object can model some part of reality or can be an invention of the design process whose collaborations with other such objects serve as the mechanisms that provide some higher-level behavior.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] Put another way, an object represents an individual, identifiable item, unit, or entity, either real or abstract, with a well-defined role in the problem domain.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] A programming language can be classified based on its support for objects.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] A language that provides an encapsulation construct for state, behavior, and identity is classified as object-based.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] If the language also provides polymorphism and inheritance it is classified as object-oriented.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] A language that supports creating an object from a class is classified as class-based.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] A language that supports object creation via a template object is classified as prototype-based.
[src:prototype-pollution/object-computer-science] In purely object-oriented programming languages, such as Java and C#, all classes might be part of an inheritance tree such that the root class is `Object`, meaning all objects instances of `Object` or implicitly extend `Object`.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Prototype-based programming uses the process generalized objects, which can then be cloned and extended.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Using fruit as an example, a "fruit" object would represent the properties and functionality of fruit in general.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] A "banana" object would be cloned from the "fruit" object and general properties specific to bananas would be appended.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Each individual "banana" object would be cloned from the generic "banana" object.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Compare to the class-based paradigm, where a "fruit" *class* would be extended by a "banana" *class*.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The first prototype-based programming language was Daniel G.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Other early prototype systems include Director a.k.a.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Ani (on top of MacLisp) (1976-1979), and contemporaneously and not independently, ThingLab (on top of Smalltalk) (1977-1981), respective PhD projects by Kenneth Michael Kahn at MIT and Alan Hamilton Borning at Stanford (but working with Alan Kay at Xerox PARC).
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Hewitt's Actors team at MIT added support for Prototype OO to ACT-1 in 1979 based on Kahn's work, calling the underlying mechanism "delegation" to distinguish it from the Class OO support they also added as "inheritance".
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Borning popularized the word "prototype" in this context in his 1981 paper in *ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems (TOPLAS)*.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Meanwhile, Rees and Adams's implemented class-less OO using lexical closures in Yale T Scheme (1981-1989)—they didn't say "prototype", but it was isomorphic.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Ken Dickey later published their OO model as portable Scheme code in 1992 as YASOS.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Now, the language that made the name and notion of prototypes popular among academics was Self (1985-1995), developed by David Ungar and Randall Smith.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] But the language that made prototypes ubiquitous for everyone was Brendan Eich's JavaScript (1995-ongoing).
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Since the late 1990s, the classless paradigm has grown increasingly popular.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Some current prototype-oriented languages are JavaScript (and other ECMAScript implementations such as JScript and Flash's ActionScript 1.0), Lua, Cecil, NewtonScript, Io, Ioke, MOO, REBOL and AHK.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Both languages are used to define large distributed software configurations (Jsonnet being directly inspired by GCL, the Google Configuration Language, with which Google defines all its deployments, and has similar semantics though with dynamic binding of variables).
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Since then, other languages like Gerbil Scheme have implemented pure functional lazy prototype systems based on similar principles.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Etymologically, a "prototype" means "first cast" ("cast" in the sense of being manufactured).
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] A prototype is a concrete thing, from which other objects can be created by copying and modifying.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] For example, the International Prototype of the Kilogram is an actual object that really exists, from which new kilogram-objects can be created by copying.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In comparison, a "class" is an abstract thing, in which objects can belong.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] For example, all kilogram-objects are in the class of KilogramObject, which might be a subclass of MetricObject, and so on.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Advocates of prototype-based programming argue that it encourages the programmer to focus on the behavior of some set of examples and only later worry about classifying these objects into archetypal objects that are later used in a fashion similar to classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Almost all prototype-based systems are based on interpreted and dynamically typed languages.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Systems based on statically typed languages are technically feasible, however.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In prototype-based languages there are no explicit classes.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Objects inherit directly from other objects through a prototype property.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The prototype property is called `prototype` in Self and JavaScript, or `proto` in Io.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] There are two methods of constructing new objects: *ex nihilo* ("from nothing") object creation or through *cloning* an existing object.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The former is supported through some form of object literal, declarations where objects can be defined at runtime through special syntax such as `{...}` and passed directly to a variable.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] While most systems support a variety of cloning, *ex nihilo* object creation is not as prominent.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In class-based languages, a new instance is constructed through a class's constructor function, a special function that reserves a block of memory for the object's members (properties and methods) and returns a reference to that block.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] An optional set of constructor arguments can be passed to the function and are usually held in properties.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The resulting instance will inherit all the methods and properties that were defined in the class, which acts as a kind of template from which similarly typed objects can be constructed.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Systems that support *ex nihilo* object creation allow new objects to be created from scratch without cloning from an existing prototype.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Such systems provide a special syntax for specifying the properties and behaviors of new objects without referencing existing objects.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In many prototype languages there exists a root object, often called *Object*, which is set as the default prototype for all other objects created in run-time and which carries commonly needed methods such as a `toString()` function to return a description of the object as a string.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] One useful aspect of *ex nihilo* object creation is to ensure that a new object's slot (properties and methods) names do not have namespace conflicts with the top-level *Object* object.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] (In the JavaScript language, one can do this by using a null prototype, i.e.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In prototype-based languages that use *delegation*, the language runtime is capable of dispatching the correct method or finding the right piece of data simply by following a series of delegation pointers (from object to its prototype) until a match is found.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] All that is required to establish this behavior-sharing between objects is the delegation pointer.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Unlike the relationship between class and instance in class-based object-oriented languages, the relationship between the prototype and its offshoots does not require that the child object have a memory or structural similarity to the prototype beyond this link.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] As such, the child object can continue to be modified and amended over time without rearranging the structure of its associated prototype as in class-based systems.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] It is also important to note that not only data, but also methods can be added or changed.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] For this reason, some prototype-based languages refer to both data and methods as "slots" or "members".
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] In *concatenative* prototyping - the approach implemented by the Kevo programming language - there are no visible pointers or links to the original prototype from which an object is cloned.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The prototype (parent) object is copied rather than linked to and there is no delegation.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] As a result, changes to the prototype will not be reflected in cloned objects.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Incidentally, the Cosmos programming language achieves the same through the use of persistent data structures.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] The main conceptual difference under this arrangement is that changes made to a prototype object are not automatically propagated to clones.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] This may be seen as an advantage or disadvantage.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] More sophisticated implementations can avoid this problem, however, although trade-offs between speed and memory are required.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] For example, systems with concatenative prototyping can use a copy-on-write implementation to allow for behind-the-scenes data sharing — and such an approach is indeed followed by Kevo.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Conversely, systems with delegation-based prototyping can use caching to speed up data lookup.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Advocates of class-based object models who criticize prototype-based systems often have concerns similar to the concerns that proponents of static type systems for programming languages have of dynamic type systems (see datatype).
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Usually, such concerns involve correctness, safety, predictability, efficiency and programmer unfamiliarity.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] On the first three points, classes are often seen as analogous to types (in most statically typed object-oriented languages they serve that role) and are proposed to provide contractual guarantees to their instances, and to users of their instances, that they will behave in some given fashion.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] Regarding efficiency, declaring classes simplifies many compiler optimizations that allow developing efficient method and instance-variable lookup.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] For the Self language, much development time was spent on developing, compiling, and interpreting techniques to improve the performance of prototype-based systems versus class-based systems.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] A common criticism made against prototype-based languages is that the community of software developers is unfamiliar with them, despite the popularity and market permeation of JavaScript.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] However, knowledge about prototype-based systems is increasing with the proliferation of JavaScript frameworks and the complex use of JavaScript as the World Wide Web (Web) matures.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-based-programming] ECMAScript 6 introduced classes as syntactic sugar over JavaScript's existing prototype-based inheritance, providing an alternative way to create objects and manage inheritance.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] Prototype Pollution is a critical vulnerability that can allow attackers to manipulate an application's JavaScript objects and properties, leading to serious security issues such as unauthorized access to data, privilege escalation, and even remote code execution.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] For examples of why this is dangerous, see the links in the Other resources section below.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] You can also use the `Object.freeze()` and `Object.seal()` APIs to prevent built-in prototypes from being modified however this can break the application if the libraries they use modify the built-in prototypes.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] Node.js also offers the ability to remove the `__proto__` property completely using the `--disable-proto=delete` flag.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] Note this is a defense in depth measure.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] Prototype pollution is still possible using `constructor.prototype` properties but removing `__proto__` helps reduce attack surface and prevent certain attacks.
[src:prototype-pollution/prototype-pollution-prevention-cheat-sheet] Credit to Gareth Hayes for providing the original protection guidance in this comment.
